tizzy up
Homonym Number:
Word Class: verb
Sense Number:
Definition:make (a person or thing) more attractive or showy; (without object) smarten up, dress up.
Origin: [none]
Register: informal

Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: often as tizzied up adjective
Citations
Date:  0/0/1988
Source:  Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author:  McGILL
Vol / Page:  113
Edition:
Quote:  <i>tizzy up</i> dress up for an outing; probably derived from `titivate'; eg `Well, ladies, are you going to go and tizzy up before we leave?' NZA.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1995
Source:  Gold in the Creek
Author:  McGill
Vol / Page:  249
Edition:
Quote:  And, if Ron was interested, he had rescued all those old tin cigarette and petrol and soap signs from the tip, if he wanted to tizzy up his store frontage.
